\label{COR: rep variety}
Suppose $M$ and $N$ are compact 3-manifolds with incompressible toral boundaries, and  $f:\widehat{\pi_1M}\to \widehat{\pi_1N}$ is a  peripheral regular isomorphism. 
Then, there is a homeomorphism $\Psi: \partial M\to \partial N$ such that the images of the restriction maps \iffalse$$\mathscr X(M)\to\mathscr X(\partial_1M)\times\cdots\times\mathscr X(\partial _nM)\quad \text{and}\quad \mathscr X(N)\to\mathscr X(\partial_1N)\times\cdots\times\mathscr X(\partial _nN)$$\fi $\mathscr{X}_n(M)\to \mathscr{X}_n(\partial M)$ and $\mathscr{X}_n(N)\to \mathscr{X}_n(\partial N)$ are identical through $\Psi$.

\label{RMK: A-polynomial}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]

\item\label{rmk2} Reversing the orientation of $K$ does not change $A_K$. However, reversing the orientation of the ambient space $S^3$ changes $A_K$; to be precise, $A_{\overline{K}}(M,L)\doteq A_{K}(M^{-1},L)$ where $\overline{K}$ is the mirror image of $K$, see \cite[Proposition 4.2]{CL96}.
\item\label{rmk3} There are slight differences in the definition of $A$-polynomials among different literatures. In our definition, the $A$-polynomial does not have repeated factors, and always contains $L-1$ as a factor. 
\end{enumerate}

\label{PROP: mixed peripheral regular}
