\label{LEM: extend}
Let $G$ be a finitely generated group, and let $\rho: G\to \SL(n,\C)$ be a representation, where $n\in \mathbb{N}$. 
\iffalse
Then, $\phi$ extends to $\widehat{G}$, that is, there exists a representation (i.e. a homomorphism of abstract groups) $\Phi: \widehat{G}\to \SL(2,\C)$ such that the following diagram commutes.
\begin{equation*}
\begin{tikzcd}
G \arrow[rd, "\iota_G"'] \arrow[rrrd, "\phi"] &                                &  &             \\
                                              & \widehat{G} \arrow[rr, "\Phi"] &  & {\SL(n,\C)}
\end{tikzcd}
\end{equation*}
\fi
Then there exists a profinite group $\Pi$, a homomorphism $\phi: G\to \Pi$, a continuous homomorphism $\Phi: \widehat{G}\to \Pi$, and an injective homomorphism $\varsigma:\Pi\to \SL(n,\C)$ which is not necessarily continuous, such that the following diagram commutes. 
\begin{equation*}
\usebox{\rep}
\end{equation*}

nodes.proof:
It is shown in \cite[Lemma 4.2]{BMRS20} (though only stated for $\SL(2,\C)$ representations, but also works for $\SL(n,\C)$-representations) that there exist some prime number $p$ and a field isomorphism (which is not continuous in the classical topology) $\theta: \C\to \overline{\Q_p}$ such that the representation
\begin{equation*}
\begin{tikzcd}
\theta_\ast \rho:\; G\arrow[r,"\rho"] & \SL(n,\C) \arrow[r,"\theta","\cong"'] & \SL(n,\overline{\Q_p})
\end{tikzcd}
\end{equation*}
is bounded, that is, the matrix entries in $\mathrm{im}(\theta_{\ast}\rho)$ is bounded with respect to the unique $p$-adic norm. 

Since $G$ is finitely generated, there exists a finite extension $K$ of $\Q_p$ such that $\mathrm{im}(\theta_{\ast}\rho)\subseteq \SL(n,K)$.
Since $K$ is finite over $\Q_p$, $K$ is a complete and locally compact metric space, and so is $\SL(n,K)$. Thus, the boundness of $\theta_\ast\rho$ implies that the closure $\overline{\mathrm{im}(\theta_{\ast}\rho)}$ in $\SL(n,K)$ is compact. Moreover, $K$ is totally disconnected, and so is $\SL(n,K)$. Therefore, the topological group $\overline{\mathrm{im}(\theta_{\ast}\rho)}$  is compact, Hausdorff, and totally disconnected, which is thus a profinite group according to \autoref{PROP: Top}. 

Let $\Pi= \overline{\mathrm{im}(\theta_{\ast}\rho)}$ be the profinite group. Define 
\begin{equation*}
\begin{tikzcd}
\varsigma: \Pi \arrow[r, hook] & \SL(n,K) \arrow[r,hook] & \SL(n,\Q_p) \arrow[r,"\theta^{-1}","\cong"'] & \SL(n,\C)
\end{tikzcd}
\end{equation*}
and
\begin{equation*}
\begin{tikzcd}
\phi: G \arrow[r, "\theta_\ast\rho"] & \mathrm{im}(\theta_{\ast}\rho) \arrow[r,hook] & \Pi.
\end{tikzcd}
\end{equation*}
Then, the universal property of profinite completion \cite[Lemma 3.2.1]{RZ10} implies that the homomorphism $\phi: G\to \Pi$ extends to a continuous homomorphism $\Psi:\widehat{G}\to \Pi$ such that $\Phi\circ \iota_{G}=\phi$. 
\iffalse In particular, we have the following commutative diagram.
\begin{equation*}
\begin{tikzcd}[column sep=tiny]
G \arrow[rrd, "\iota_G"] \arrow[rrrr, "\theta_{\ast}\phi"] &  &                                               &  & \overline{\mathrm{im}(\theta_\ast\phi)} \arrow[r, symbol=\subseteq] & {\SL(2,K)} \arrow[rrr, hook] &                                    &  & {\SL(2,\overline{\Q_p})} \\
                                                           &  & \widehat{G} \arrow[rru, "\Psi"] \arrow[rrrr,"\Phi=\theta^{-1}\circ \Psi"] &  &                                                   &                                & {\SL(2,\C)} \arrow[rru, "\theta","\cong"'] &  &                         
\end{tikzcd}
\end{equation*}
Thus, the homomorphism (which is not necessarily continuous) $\Phi=\theta^{-1}\circ \Psi: \widehat{G}\to \SL(2,\C)$ satisfies the requirement.  
\fi
Thus, we have obtained the commutative diagram in the statement of this lemma.

